issue.title: Phase 3: AI Training Pipeline
issue.body:
## Overview
Build a comprehensive AI training pipeline for custom model fine-tuning, dataset management, A/B testing, and performance evaluation to optimize agent capabilities.

## Technical Requirements

### Core Features
- **Custom Model Fine-tuning**
  - Transfer learning support
  - Hyperparameter optimization
  - Distributed training
  - Model versioning
  - Checkpoint management
  - Incremental learning

- **Dataset Management**
  - Data ingestion pipeline
  - Annotation tools
  - Data versioning
  - Quality validation
  - Privacy compliance
  - Synthetic data generation

- **A/B Testing Framework**
  - Experiment design
  - Traffic splitting
  - Statistical analysis
  - Feature flags
  - Rollback mechanisms
  - Performance comparison

- **Performance Evaluation**
  - Automated benchmarking
  - Custom metrics
  - Model comparison
  - Regression detection
  - Bias detection
  - Explainability tools

### Technical Architecture
```typescript
interface TrainingPipeline {
  dataLoader: DataLoader;
  preprocessor: DataPreprocessor;
  trainer: ModelTrainer;
  evaluator: ModelEvaluator;
  deployer: ModelDeployer;
  monitor: ModelMonitor;
}

interface MLOpsFramework {
  experiments: ExperimentTracker;
  registry: ModelRegistry;
  serving: ModelServing;
  monitoring: PerformanceMonitor;
  governance: ModelGovernance;
  infrastructure: ComputeCluster;
}

interface Dataset {
  id: string;
  version: string;
  schema: DataSchema;
  splits: TrainTestSplit;
  annotations: Annotation[];
  metadata: DatasetMetadata;
  privacy: PrivacyConfig;
}
```

### Implementation Requirements
1. **Training Infrastructure**
   - GPU cluster management
   - Distributed training (Horovod/DDP)
   - Auto-scaling
   - Resource scheduling
   - Cost optimization
   - Spot instance management

2. **MLOps Pipeline**
   - CI/CD for ML
   - Automated testing
   - Model validation
   - Deployment automation
   - Monitoring & alerting
   - Drift detection

3. **Data Pipeline**
   - ETL workflows
   - Data validation
   - Feature engineering
   - Data augmentation
   - Privacy preservation
   - Compliance checks

## Platform Components
- **Training Dashboard**
  - Experiment tracking
  - Metrics visualization
  - Resource monitoring
  - Cost tracking
  - Model comparison
  - Hyperparameter tuning

- **Data Management**
  - Dataset browser
  - Annotation interface
  - Version control
  - Quality metrics
  - Lineage tracking
  - Access control

- **Model Registry**
  - Model catalog
  - Version management
  - Metadata storage
  - Approval workflow
  - Deployment tracking
  - Performance history

## ML Frameworks Support
- **Deep Learning**
  - TensorFlow/Keras
  - PyTorch
  - JAX
  - Hugging Face Transformers

- **Classical ML**
  - Scikit-learn
  - XGBoost/LightGBM
  - CatBoost
  - AutoML tools

- **Infrastructure**
  - Kubernetes
  - Kubeflow
  - MLflow
  - Ray
  - Apache Airflow

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Support for 5+ ML frameworks
- [ ] Distributed training across 100+ GPUs
- [ ] Dataset versioning with Git-like interface
- [ ] A/B testing with statistical significance
- [ ] Model training <24 hours for large models
- [ ] Automated model evaluation pipeline
- [ ] Model registry with 1000+ models
- [ ] Real-time performance monitoring
- [ ] Cost optimization saving 30%+

## Performance Requirements
- Training throughput >10TB/day
- Model serving <50ms latency
- 99.9% training job success rate
- Auto-scaling in <2 minutes
- Dataset loading <30 seconds
- Experiment tracking for 10,000+ runs

## Priority
**P3** - Future enhancement for advanced AI

## Estimated Effort
10 weeks (4 ML engineers + 2 DevOps)

## Technical Lead
@David_Chen - ML operations expertise required

## Related Issues
- Requires GPU infrastructure
- Integrates with model serving
- Connects to monitoring system
- Links to cost management

If it's given a timestamp that's in the past (as happened here), it'll just return without adding the timer to the queue. Further, fixing that wouldn't have made this setup work either, because it's not possible to schedule a timer while it's still active (which was the case here because the timer was being rescheduled from within itself).

To still get the benefits that that commit was trying to get, we now use a separate thread rather than a timer (and this approach actually works).

I've also included an optimization for `sys$recvmsg`, which makes WindowServer disappear from the kmalloc stack dumps when it's idle (though there's a bunch of other stuff, mainly to do with SysFS, that still makes the system quite slow when running with those enabled).

beta build 150.1

1. enter a sector (Serpulo) that has an enemy base
